Thanks, Felix! Yours and Peter's comments gave me a new path for
investigation. I logged into Gnome using X11, rather than Wayland, and
now I'm using the intel driver:

    > inxi -Gxx
    Graphics:
    =C2=A0 Device-1: Intel UHD Graphics 620 vendor: CLEVO/KAPOK driver: i=
915
    =C2=A0 v: kernel bus ID: 00:02.0 chip ID: 8086:3ea0
    =C2=A0 Device-2: Chicony Chicony USB2.0 Camera type: USB driver: uvcv=
ideo
    =C2=A0 bus ID: 1-7:3 chip ID: 04f2:b649
    =C2=A0 Display: x11 server: X.Org 1.20.8 compositor: gnome-shell driv=
er:
    intel
    =C2=A0 unloaded: fbdev,modesetting,vesa resolution: 1920x1080~60Hz s-=
dpi: 96
    =C2=A0 OpenGL: renderer: Mesa DRI Intel UHD Graphics 620 (WHL GT2)
    =C2=A0 v: 4.6 Mesa 20.1.4 compat-v: 3.0 direct render: Yes=20


So it seems that Wayland doesn't use the intel DDX if it's installed,
but X11 does. I'll run like this for a while to see how it goes. If it
goes OK, I'll switch back to the modesetting DDX but stay with X11 to
see if its the DDX or Wayland.

Specific comments below.

David


